10","1355":"1355","1354":"1354","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1430":"1430","1409":"1409","about 1385":"about 1385","26 July 1409":"26 July 1409","8 August 1420":"8 August 1420","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Icomb, Gloucestershire, England":"Icomb, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Beaupyne was born about 1385, her father, Thomas Beaupenny, was 32 and her mother, Margaret de la Mere, was 32. She married John Blackett in 1409, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died on 8 August 1420, in England, at the age of 36."},"et":{"about 1385–8 August 1420":"umbes 1385–8. august 1420","1380–1442":"1380–1442","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1381–1430":"1381–1430","1412–1442":"1412–1442","1354–1410":"1354–1410","1355–1409":"1355–1409","1385":"1385","1381":"1381","1380":"1380","1412":"1412","1410":"1410","1355":"1355","1354":"1354","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1430":"1430","1409":"1409","about 1385":"umbes 1385","26 July 1409":"26. juuli 1409","8 August 1420":"8. august 1420","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Icomb, Gloucestershire, England":"Icomb, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1385–8 August 1420":"noin 1385–8. elokuuta 1420","1380–1442":"1380–1442","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1381–1430":"1381–1430","1412–1442":"1412–1442","1354–1410":"1354–1410","1355–1409":"1355–1409","1385":"1385","1381":"1